                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/2210a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-10-16T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 16, 1931—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>94. Since the receipt today of the invitation from the Council for you to attend
                    its meetings I think it well to repeat, for the purpose of absolute clarity,
                    your instructions, which are as follows:</p>
                <p>You are authorized to participate in the discussions of the Council when they
                    relate to the possible application of the Kellogg-Briand Pact, to which treaty
                    the United States is a party. You are expected to report the result of such
                    discussions to the Department for its determination as to possible action. If
                    you are present at the discussion of any other aspect of the Chinese-Japanese
                    dispute, it must be only as an observer and auditor.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
